%I A395013 #23 Apr 20 2026 18:30:29
%S A395013 225,315,525,675,735,855,1125,1155
%N A395013 Deficient numbers k for which the k-th Fibonacci number is abundant.
%C A395013 All terms known so far (up to 1155) are multiples of 15, will this always be true? - _M. F. Hasler_, Apr 11 2026
%C A395013 From _Alexander Violette_, Apr 14 2026: (Start)
%C A395013 1485, 1995, and 9975 are terms of this sequence.
%C A395013 If k is a term, then all numbers of the form k*x where k*x is deficient are part of this sequence. (End)
%e A395013 a(1) = 225 is a term because 225 is a deficient number as the sum of the aliquot divisors of 225, i.e., 1 + 3 + 5 + 9 + 15 + 25 + 45 + 75 = 178, is less than 225, and 225th Fibonacci number, i.e., 47068900554068939361891195233676009091941690850 is an abundant number.
%o A395013 (PARI) is_A395013(n)=sigma(n,-1)<2&&sigma(fibonacci(n),-1)>2 \\ _M. F. Hasler_, Apr 11 2026
